  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation in
scalarizeBinopOrCmp turns a vector sdiv using an insertelement with an
out-of-range index into a scalar sdiv followed by an insertelement. Original
IR:\n  %ins = insertelement <2 x i8> poison, i8 %x, i32 3\n  %bo = sdiv <2 x i8>
%ins, <i8 5, i8 2>\nBecause the insertelement index (3) is out-of-range for a <2
x i8> vector, %ins is entirely poison and the vector sdiv produces a poison
vector with no possibility of UB (the divisor elements are defined constants 5
and 2). After transformation:\n  %bo.scalar = sdiv i8 %x, poison\n  %bo =
insertelement <2 x i8> poison, i8 %bo.scalar, i64 3\nThis introduces a scalar
sdiv where the divisor operand is poison. Since sdiv has undefined behavior if
the divisor is zero, using a poison divisor (which may be zero) makes the target
strictly less defined than the source. Alive2 correctly reports: Source is more
defined than target.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe first and only
transformation occurs in scalarizeBinopOrCmp. No other passes interfere. The
pattern match captures the insertelement-with-constant-vector form and proceeds
to scalarize. Cost model allows transformation. The log shows the transformed IR
exactly as produced by lines 1007\u20131029 of the function.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nWithin scalarizeBinopOrCmp, the code determines Index as the insertion
index from the non-constant side:\n  uint64_t Index = IsConst0 ? Index1 :
Index0;\nFor a single insertelement against a constant full vector (our case:
left operand has an insertelement, right operand is a constant vector), IsConst1
== true, IsConst0 == false, so Index = Index0 = 3.\nLater, for constant sides, it
extracts a scalar element using:\n  if (IsConst1)\n    V1 =
ConstantExpr::getExtractElement(VecC1, Builder.getInt64(Index));\nSince Index = 3
and the constant vector <i8 5, i8 2> has only 2 elements, this extraction yields
a poison constant. That poison is then used as the divisor of a newly created
scalar sdiv. Division by poison may incur UB because poison is not guaranteed to
satisfy the non-zero precondition of sdiv.\nThe original code path never
evaluated any scalar sdiv with a potentially zero divisor; thus the transform
introduces UB.\nMissing safeguard: The transformation assumes the chosen Index is
valid for any constant vector operand; it does not check for out-of-range indices
created by insertelement poisoning the entire vector. In such cases, scalarizing
the operation is either meaningless (result is known poison) or dangerous
(introduces UB in ops like sdiv, udiv, srem, urem, shifts, etc.).\n\n4. Proposed
Edit Point(s):\nAdd a bounds check after computing Index and before using it for
cost modeling/extraction. If Index is out-of-range for the fixed vector type,
bail out (return false) to prevent scalarization. This preserves correctness by
leaving original semantics (poison vector) without introducing potentially UB
scalar operations.\nEdit at lines 963\u2013972 (after Index, ScalarTy, VecTy
acquisition) inserting:\n  // Do not scalarize if the insertion index is
out-of-range. In the original\n  // IR, an out-of-range insertelement makes the
entire vector operand poison,\n  // and the vector operation produces poison
without triggering UB. Creating\n  // a scalar op with a poison operand (e.g. as
a divisor for sdiv) could\n  // introduce undefined behavior. Bail out instead.\n
if (auto *FVT = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(VecTy)) {\n    if (Index >=
FVT->getNumElements())\n      return false;\n  }\nThis is minimal, prevents the
faulty transformation, and avoids needing more invasive changes (like selectively
replacing the scalar op with a poison value).\n\nRationale: Checking before
extraction avoids creating poison operands for potentially UB-sensitive scalar
operations. It maintains profitability decisions only for valid indices.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe bug arises from using an out-of-range vector index to extract a
scalar from a constant vector, producing a poison divisor for sdiv and
introducing UB. Adding a bounds check to bail on out-of-range indices prevents
the transformation in such cases, preserving correctness. This fix is narrow,
safe, and aligned with existing design (early exits on unsafe patterns).",
